Hi,

We had a temporary autonomous routine in Robot.Java but I have updated our code to use commands and subsystems. The timer seems to work and our drive_forward() and turn_right() commands work. The problem I’m facing now is that I’m calling autonomous.execute() in autonomousPeriodic within Robot.Java when I enable autonomous on the driver station the motors will start and stop rapidly and it’s not a consistent smooth motion. I’m not sure if it is the way I’m calling the autonomous command but I would appreciate it if somebody could look at my code to see if there is anything wrong with it.

GitHub Repo

Thank you!

You shouldn’t be calling .execute() directly on a command. The idea behind commands is that they get scheduled (see autonomousInit) and are automatically run through the lifecycle by the scheduler (see robotPeriodic).

You should not have an “Autonomous Subsystem” that tries to run the same motors as another subsystem. If you don’t get a fatal error, you will have two subsystems competing to control the same motors.

Your autonomous command(s) should use the same subsystems as your teleop commands.

You are creating two instance of your Autonomous command.

  • The instance called m_autonomousCommand is being scheduled properly by Robot.autonomousInit().
  • The instance called autonomous is not being scheduled, and it’s being improperly accessed by Robot.autonomousInit() and Robot.autonomousPeriodic().

I highly recommend you read and understand the Structuring a Command-Based Robot Project documentation.

  1. You should not have a static instance of RobotContainer on Robot.
  2. You should have your commands and subsystems private within RobotContainer.
  3. You should pass the required subsystems into the Commands that need them, not try to reach out and get them from Robot/RobotContainer. (Find the documentation section that mentions “dependency injection” for an example.)
